  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Helps detect and prevent money laundering\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Makes money laundering a federal crime\n- Prohibits conducting financial transactions with proceeds from illegal activities\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements and monitoring of financial transactions\n- Strengthened measures to prevent terrorist financing\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing anti-money laundering laws\n- Enhanced whistleblower protections\n- Expanded regulations on cryptocurrency and digital assets\n\nThese federal statutes provide legal frameworks for:\n- Detecting and preventing money laundering\n- Imposing criminal penalties\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious activities\n- Establishing guidelines for investigating financial crimes\n\nPenalties can include substantial fines and imprisonment for individuals and organizations found guilty of money laundering.",
